Tree Re-rooting Technique (DP on Trees)

Tree rerooting is an advanced dynamic programming technique used on trees to compute answers for every node as root efficiently.

Instead of recalculating the whole DFS for every root (O(N²)), rerooting computes all answers in O(N).

1. What is Re-rooting?

Normally in trees, we assume one node is the root (say node 0).

Re-rooting means:

“If the root changes from one node to another, how does the answer change?”

It helps solve problems like:

Sum of distances from every node
Maximum subtree values
Number of paths
Tree DP for every root
Longest distance from each node
Contribution techniques
2. Basic Idea

We usually do:

First DFS

Compute information for subtree.

Second DFS

Move root from parent → child and update answers.

3. Classic Example: Sum of Distances from Every Node

Given a tree of n nodes.

For every node u, compute:

ans[u]=∑distance(u,v)
4. Naive Solution

Run BFS/DFS from every node.

Complexity:

O(N
2
)

Too slow for large trees.

5. Optimized Re-rooting Solution

We use:

sub[u] → size of subtree
dp[u] → sum of distances inside subtree
ans[u] → final answer for node u
6. First DFS

We compute:

subtree size
sum of distances in subtree

Formula:

dp[u]+=dp[v]+sub[v]

because every node in child subtree becomes 1 farther from u.

Code
static ArrayList<Integer>[] g;
static int[] sub;
static int[] dp;

static void dfs1(int u, int p) {
    sub[u] = 1;

    for (int v : g[u]) {
        if (v == p) continue;

        dfs1(v, u);

        sub[u] += sub[v];

        dp[u] += dp[v] + sub[v];
    }
}
